Insufficient Draft

Advice

Try to maintain uniform thickness.

Adjust draft angle. In general, ribs should be 50% of thickness.

Knife Edge Threshold

Advice

Decrease thickness in thicker regions.
Adjust draft angle. In general, ribs should be 50% of thickness.
Use a tool like Shell to core out thick sections to maintain uniform thickness.
Manage Plastic Rules to verify the Thickness Range is defined correctly for the plastic material.
Displays only the thickness alerts for regions that are thicker than the upper limit of the Thickness Range defined in the plastic rule.

Too Thick

Regions that are too thick take longer to cool.This can lead to longer manufacturing cycle times.Slower cooling can cause uneven shrinkage and sink marks, which warp the part as the molten plastic solidifies.

Advice

Increase thickness in thinner regions.
Adjust draft angle. In general, ribs should be 50% of thickness.
Manage Plastic Rules to verify the Thickness Range is defined correctly for the plastic material.
Displays only the thickness alerts for regions that are thinner than the lower limit of the Thickness Range defined in the plastic rule.

Too Thin

Regions that are too thin may fill slower or have difficulty filling completely.They cool faster than thicker regions.This can cause uneven shrinkage, which warps the part as the molten plastic solidifies.

Advice

Remove undercuts to simplify the mold design.
Confirm pull direction.
Redesign undercut features to align with the pull direction.
Check draft on the undercut feature.
Investigate to make sure the part can be removed from the mold.
Highlight undercuts as features of concern, and consult a mold designer. Confirm whether sliders, lifters, or inserts could be added to the mold to help remove the part.
Undercuts: %1% %2% undercuts that will interfere with ejection from a mold.

Undercuts

Undercuts are trapped features that can't be ejected from the mold. If the mold requires sliders, lifters, or inserts to help eject the part from the mold, it may increase the cost. Not all undercuts can be avoided, but they should be minimized.
